To investigate the effect of SAA-LBL-type morphology on charge generation process and explain higher Jsc of SAA-LBL-type devices, time-resolved absorption measurements are carried out. 800 nm is used as excitation wavelength to selectively excite the acceptors in D:A blend films. The results shown in Fig. 7a–f display the photo-induced bleaching (PB) of three structures. After excitation, the PB signals of Y6 located at 810 nm gradually descends, meanwhile, increased PB signals of PM6 at 630 nm could be observed. This clearly shows hole transfer from acceptor to donor. Among them, SAA-LBL-type has strongest intensity in 630 nm which means effective hole transfer, while BC-type has the weakest one. Figure S14 presents the TA traces of BC-type, LBL-type and SAA-LBL-type films at different wavelengths. Furthermore, the dynamic behaviors of hole transfer are researched by analyzing the PB signals at 630 nm versus time delay (Fig. 7g). Fitted with biexponential function, the charge transfer lifetimes could be calculated as follows. In LBL-type film, τ1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
